The synthesized wastewater containing AMO, and NaNO3 and K2HPO4·3H2O at concentrations of 273 and 40 mg/L were supplied, respectively. Similar to the AMO degradation pattern, CD-1 had the best nutrient recovery effect (Fig. 4
                        ). TN and PO4
                        3- removal after 18 days of cultivation was 82.4% and 98.7%, respectively, and their concentrations in the effluent were within the Chinese national discharge standard for municipal wastewater treatment plants. Their concentrations were also within the discharge standards of the Technology-Based Effluent Limitations in the United States (Helland, 1998) and Water Framework Directive of the European Union (Union, 1991). The TN removal was 14.6% and 9.9% higher for CD-5 and CD-1 than for the control (CD-0) lacking CDs, respectively. Thus, CD-1 increased the light energy input to microalgae, promoted the growth of microalgae, and thus led to the increased utilization of nutrients from wastewater (Yan and Zheng, 2014). The pattern of AMO degradation and nutrient removal indicated that the application of CDs provides a promising approach for coupling antibiotic wastewater treatment and microalgae cultivation.
